Exercise 14.2.5.1

In code that doesnt use stringr, youll often see paste() and paste0(). Whats the difference between the two functions? What stringr function are they equivalent to? How do the functions differ in their handling of NA?

Well, paste0 is nothing more than a paste with sep = . But because it just concatenate strings with no separator, it is runs faster. How much faster? I dont know. They are equivalent to str_c. Except str_c returns NA whenever there is an NA as an argument, while paste and paste0 transfrom NA in NA.

paste0("My favorite DataScience person is: ", NA)
## [1] "My favorite DataScience person is: NA"
str_c("My favorite DataScience person is: ", NA)
## [1] NA

Exercise 14.2.5.2

In your own words, describe the difference between the sep and collapse arguments to str_c()

They have the same goal. But sep is used between strings passed as arguments to str_c, while collapse is used between strings inside a list passed as argument. LikeL

str_c(c('This','is','separated','by','spaces'), sep = '...', collapse = ' ')
## [1] "This is separated by spaces"
str_c('This','is','separated','by','Ellipsis', sep = '...', collapse = ' ')
## [1] "This...is...separated...by...Ellipsis"

Exercise 14.2.5.4

What does str_wrap() do? When might you want to use it?

It will format a string in paragraphs of fixed width (well, tentatively fixed width, it wont break words apart). It may be used to get a better readable output of a string that was stored a single line.

Exercise 14.2.5.5

What does str_trim() do? Whats the opposite of str_trim()?

str_trim gets rid of trailing and leading whitespace. str_pad does the opposite (add leading and trailing whitespace). The first can be used to improve readability of a string, the second can be used to enforce a collection of strings to have the same length.

Exercise 14.2.5.6

Write a function that turns (e.g.) a vector c(a, b, c) into the string a, b, and c. Think carefully about what it should do if given a vector of length 0, 1, or 2

conversion <- function(vector,...){
  if(typeof(vector) != typeof(c("a"))){
    return("Hey, you didn't give me a list of chars. Follow the rules")
  }
  len <- length(vector)
  if(len == 1){
    return(vector[1])
  }
  result <- ""
  for(i in 2:len-1){
    result <- str_c(result,vector[i],", ")
  }
  return(str_c(result, "and ",vector[len]))
}
conversion(c("a","b","c"))
## [1] "a, b, and c"
conversion(c(1,2,3))
## [1] "Hey, you didn't give me a list of chars. Follow the rules"
conversion(c("a",1,"c")) # I guess R coerce to a common type
## [1] "a, 1, and c"
conversion("a","b","c") #Not how it works, but got lazy to give custom message
## [1] "a"

Exercise 14.3.1.1

Explain why each of these strings dont match a : ",\,\".

Because R is complicated. So they decided to use as a way to use a regex character as it is literal character (not the regex itself). Because is a regex, you need \ to get a single . Problem is, is a escape string, \ will actually error, since it is followed by nothing. Just adding a third one \" also does not work, because now the last is escaping behavior. It means \" is actually an unfinished string that starts with " and is yet to be finished.\ for instance, finishes that string, and is ". So to actuall get a as a pattern, you need the forth one , the first 2 says hey, here is a ", and R respondOkay, what is the regex you want to escape, and the last 2 saysescape this backslash. And then you get what you need

All that being said, pray you wont need to find a backslash. If you do, just keep adding backslashs until it works

Exercise 14.4.2.1

For each of the following challenges, try solving it by using both a single regular expression, and a combination of multiple str_detect() calls.

Let the fun begin

Find all words that start or end with x.

start_end_x <- function(string){
  answer <- c()
  pattern1 <- '^[xX]'
  pattern2 <- '[xX]$'
  words <- str_split(string," ")
  for(word in words){
    string_check <- str_detect(word,pattern1) | str_detect(word,pattern2)
    answer <- string_check
  }
  return(words[[1]][which(answer)])
}
start_end_x("Xanax Xerox xylophone sax fax text mixer all words have x")
## [1] "Xanax"     "Xerox"     "xylophone" "sax"       "fax"       "x"

Find all words that start with a vowel and end with a consonant.

start_end_vowel <- function(string){
  answer <- c()
  pattern1 <- '^[aeiouAEIOU]'
  pattern2 <- '[^aeiouAEIOU]$'
  words <- str_split(string," ")
  for(word in words){
    string_check <- str_detect(word,pattern1) & str_detect(word,pattern2)
    answer <- string_check
  }
  return(words[[1]][which(answer)])
}
start_end_vowel("Apple apples IdioT ostricH are nice words and Y is not a vowel")
## [1] "apples"  "IdioT"   "ostricH" "and"     "is"

Are there any words that contain at least one of each different vowel?

contain_vowels <- function(string){
  answer <- FALSE
  pattern1 <- '[aA]'
  pattern2 <- '[eE]'
  pattern3 <- '[iI]'
  pattern4 <- '[oO]'
  pattern5 <- '[uU]'
  words <- str_split(string," ")[[1]]
  for(word in words){
    l <- str_length(word)
    string_check <- str_detect(word,pattern1) & str_detect(word,pattern2) & str_detect(word,pattern3) & str_detect(word,pattern4) & str_detect(word,pattern5)
    answer <- answer | string_check
  }
  return(answer)
}
contain_vowels("Are there any words that have all the vowels")
## [1] FALSE
contain_vowels("Unequivocally, there is")
## [1] TRUE

Exercise 14.4.2.2

What word has the highest number of vowels? What word has the highest proportion of vowels? (Hint: what is the denominator?)

count_vowels <- function(word){
  answer <- FALSE
  pattern1 <- '[aA]'
  pattern2 <- '[eE]'
  pattern3 <- '[iI]'
  pattern4 <- '[oO]'
  pattern5 <- '[uU]'
  return(str_count(word,pattern1) + str_count(word,pattern2) + str_count(word,pattern3) + str_count(word,pattern4) + str_count(word,pattern5))
}

highest_vowels <- function(string){
  words <- str_split(string," ")
  count <- c()
  for(word in words){
    count <- count_vowels(word)
  }
  return(words[[1]][which(count == max(count))])
}
highest_vowels("So many words, but which has the most number of vowels?")
## [1] "number"  "vowels?"
highest_vowels_proportion <- function(string){
  words <- str_split(string," ")
  prop <- c()
  for(word in words){
    count <- count_vowels(word)/str_length(word)
  }
  return(words[[1]][which(count == max(count))])
}
highest_vowels_proportion("So many words, but which has the most number of vowels?")
## [1] "So" "of"

Exercise 15.5.1.1

How have the proportions of people identifying as Democrat, Republican, and Independent changed over time?

It looks like a mess, even taking out No answer, dont know, other party. Despite wild movements in between, the 2014 picture looks pretty much the same as the 2000

gss_cat %>%
  group_by(year,partyid) %>%
  summarize( n = n()) %>%
  inner_join( gss_cat %>% count(year), by = c("year"), suffix = c(".group",".total")) %>%
  mutate(proportion = n.group/n.total) %>%
  filter( !(partyid %in% c("No answer", "Don't know", "Other party"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year,proportion)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = partyid))

Doing some grouping we can see a better trend of rise in independents, and decline on republicans. Democrats are stable

gss_cat %>%
  mutate(partyid = fct_recode(partyid,
                              "Republican" = "Strong republican",
                              "Republican" = "Not str republican",
                              "Independent" = "Ind,near rep",
                              "Independent" = "Ind,near dem",
                              "Independent" = "Independent",
                              "Democrat" = "Strong democrat",
                              "Democrat" = "Not str democrat",
                              "Other" = "No answer",
                              "Other" = "Don't know",
                              "Other" = "Other party")) %>%
  group_by(year,partyid) %>%
  summarize( n = n()) %>%
  inner_join( gss_cat %>% count(year), by = c("year"), suffix = c(".group",".total")) %>%
  mutate(proportion = n.group/n.total) %>%
  filter(partyid != "Other") %>%
  ggplot(aes(year,proportion)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = partyid))

Exercise 15.5.1.2

How could you collapse rincome into a small set of categories?

Using fct_collapse, instead of recode as I did above, that was a poor idea (that worked at least). As for the levels, I would combine the No answer, Dont know and Refused, also combine the bracket 5000-9999 and Less than 5000, so all the brackets have the same range (except for 25000 and more).

gss_cat %>%
  mutate(rincome = fct_collapse(rincome,
                                "other" = c("No answer","Don't know","Refused","Not applicable"),
                                "$5000 to 9999" = c("$5000 to 5999","$6000 to 6999","$7000 to 7999","$8000 to 9999"),
                                "Less than $5000" = c("$4000 to 4999","$3000 to 3999","$1000 to 2999", "Lt $1000"))) %>%
  count(rincome)
## # A tibble: 7 x 2
##           rincome     n
##            <fctr> <int>
## 1           other  8468
## 2  $25000 or more  7363
## 3  $20000 - 24999  1283
## 4  $15000 - 19999  1048
## 5  $10000 - 14999  1168
## 6   $5000 to 9999   970
## 7 Less than $5000  1183

This gives us a better sense of income distribution. Also, we should be breaking the 25k+ in more levels
